Define or Be Defined: Lessons from the Defund the Police Movement on the Power of Meaning and the Role of Definition in Polarization

By Adarsh Patel (Acknowledgements: Kaveri Pillai for her contributions in brainstorming and planning this article, and the Panorama Project Facilitators for their support, guidance, and feedback.)

Credits: Koshu Kunii (@koshuuu, Unsplash)

In late spring and early summer of 2020, as the COVID-19 pandemic kicked into high gear, millions of protesters in the U.S. and around the world took to the streets. Reacting to Minneapolis police officers grusome murder of George Floyd, they held marches, organized die-ins, and confronted officials, demanding equal justice for black people. This latest round of protests was both uniquepossibly the largest protest movement in American historyand yet firmly a continuation of the history of civil rights in America.

Like nearly all protest movements, the 2020 protesters captured the agenda and brought about a boom of policy ideas, but struggled with implementation of change as time passed. Among these policy ideas was the slogan, Defund the Police, a term that had not previously been used widely during the 2010s police brutality protests but quickly became a household term during the 2020 round of protests. Defund the Police became a controversial slogan, not only because of its orientation against the institution of policing, but also because of what some argued was its oversimplification and poor phrasing. While a slight majority of Americans supported the protests, they overwhelmingly opposed calls to Defund the Police, whatever they believed that to mean. Though a seemingly self-evident phrase, there wasand continues to besubstantial disagreement over its meaning among its already small number of proponents. This internal definitional debate in turn shaped external debate as it created opportunities for opponents of defunding, particularly partisan opponents, tointentionally or incidentallyreshape and recenter the discourse over defunding. These partisan opponents of defunding turned a seemingly non-polarizing issue (most Americans of both parties opposed defunding), into a polarizing one, or at least one with the appearance of polarization. To be sure, most Americans of both parties continue to oppose defunding, and that number has actually increased since the 2020 protests, but the discourse has focused on factual and rhetorical debate, not the merits of defunding. What has emerged is the failure of efforts to defund, yet simultaneously a contentiousor at least the appearance of a contentiousdebate over defunding. The ongoing story of Defund the Police demonstrates how politics is, in part, a struggle for the power to define, and how this battle over meaning can end in polarization, whether real or perceived.

The Birth of a New Civil Rights Movement

In many ways, despite the shocking nature of George Floyds murder, which was captured in a viral video, the 2020 protests were a reaction to something more than what happened outside the Cup Foods Grocery store at the corner of Chicago and 38th. Initial statements released by the Minneapolis Police Department, which seemed to downplay the nature of Floyds death, were pointed to as evidence of a broader problem with policing. The Department of Justice would later open a federal civil rights investigation into Minneapolis Polices policies and practices, a day after the conviction of Derek Chauvin, the officer who killed Floyd. Even the reaction of police departments to the nationwide protests last summer affirmed to many protesters that the problems with policing and the proliferation of anti-blackness were systemic.

Credits: Chris Henry (@chrishenryphoto, Unsplash)

The 2020 protests, like other recent protests, were headlined by the slogan or call to action: Black Lives Matter. This phrase began as a hashtag following the acquittal of George Zimmerman of murder charges he faced for killing Travyon Martin in 2012 and grew to national attention during the 2014 Ferguson protests over the police killing of Michael Brown, sparking a national movement. Often conflated with the Black Lives Matter organization (officially known as the Black Lives Matter Global Network Foundation), the term itself has become controversial. In any case, the Black Lives Matter movement became a sustained national and global movement for much of the early summer of 2020, a natural continuation of waves of protest over the past decade. As scholars have noted, the Black Lives Matter protests have many parallels to the 1960s Civil Rights Movement and the history of civil rights activism in the U.S., but are also unique in many dimensions, including more diversity among protesters, broader agendas, and greater decentralization.

Part of the unique nature of the Black Lives Matter movement, particularly during protests following Floyds death, is the broadly racially diverse coalition behind it. While an overwhelming majority of protesters identified as left-leaning, it has been well-documented that the American left is really a broad coalition of ideological views. In other words, the movement is likely quite ideologically diverse beyond a simple left-right divide, and anecdotal evidence seems to confirm this as well. The movement also seemingly seeks to confront racism in institutions beyond policing. The overall goals seem to be the same among the protesters: confront racism and systemic inequality. Yet, there is notable variance on the specifics of how to go about that.

Credits: Ehimetalor Akhere Unuabona (@theeastlondonphotographer, Unsplash)

The Language of the Unheard

As with other protest movements and political advocacy, certain terms and slogans, both old and new, were elevated in the discourse surrounding the Black Lives Matter protests. Black Lives Matter itself was one such slogan, but others included silence is violence, no justice, no peace, I cant breathe, say her name, and ACAB (All Cops Are Bastards). Many of these and variations of them were not unique to this wave of protests nor to civil rights protests in general. For example, ACAB originated in England in the early 1900s and then was used by racist skinheads before also being adopted by anti-racists. Nearly all of the terms were controversial given both the overall context in which they were being used and the calls to action that some of them implied. Arguably, the phrase that most stood out and was most uniquely controversial during the 2020 protests was Defund the Police.

Defund the Police At Glance

The term Defund the Policelike many 21st century political phrasesrose to the national attention as a hashtag that turned into a protest slogan. However, unlike other slogans, like Black Lives Matter, it seemed to advocate, at least from a surface-level perspective, for a specific policy action: divestment from the institution of policing as it currently exists. This basic policy idea drew its origins from 20th century figures like W.E.B. DuBois, who promoted abolition-democracydismantling institutions of oppressionand Angela Davis, who promoted abolition feminisman intersectional approach of dismantling institutions of oppression. Despite this history and the seemingly self-evident meaning of Defund the Police, there is

substantial divergence within the movement over what the term means in practice. As the protests of summer 2020 began to taper off, and a wave of gun violence and homicides arrived in 2021, it became apparent that mainstream calls to Defund the Police had lost momentum, and the underlying disagreements over what the term means were more clearly exposed.

Credits: Nathan Dumlao (@nate_dumlao, Unsplash)

The Internal Definitional Debate over Defund the Police

Assessing the internal debate over the meaning of Defund the Police is critical to understanding the policy clash it has produced and how the discourse surrounding it has contributed to continued polarization. In some sense, it is difficult to even lump together various definitions of the term because nearly every proponent of defunding has a nuanced meaning for it that differs from their peers meaning for it. Nevertheless, some basic categories of definitions can be used to understand the divergence in interpretations of Defund the Police.

1.Abolish the Police

The definition of Defund the Police as Abolish the Police is arguably the most radical definition, but it is one that has a storied history among persistent civil rights advocates. As the origins of Defund the Police from the ideas of abolition-democracy and abolition feminism demonstrate, many civil rights thinkers have long called for an abolition-focus in their movements. Police abolition grew out of the 20th century prison abolition movement. This policy orientation has been boosted by more recent calls to Abolish ICE, referring to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement.

Most often, abolitionistsgiven their strong viewsseem to directly use the phrase

Abolish the Police, but some have used Defund the Police almost interchangeably with Abolish the Police. Moreover, some proponents of Defund the Police define it in such a way that they basically mean Abolish the Police, i.e., defund them into non-existence. Abolitionists see defunding the police as an opportunity not to re-imagine policing, but rather to fundamentally re-imagine how society deals with harm and conflict. They are often in favor of broader decriminalization and alternative methods of harm prevention and reduction such as restorative justice and counseling. To this subset of defunding proponents, Defund the Police means completely eliminating the institution along with the broader criminal justice system.

2.Reform the Police

The least radical definition among defunding proponents is arguably that of reforming the police. Supporters who follow this definition of Defund the Police see it as simply a new term to describe the various reforms of policing that have been routinely demanded over the last decade or so. Although the basic premise of most supporters of defunding is that reform does not work and therefore defunding is necessary, supporters who subscribe to the reform definition are essentially just borrowing the term to push for familiar change.

3.Rebuild the Police

Between the reform and abolitionist definitions lie a variety of other definitions, including the rebuilding definition of Defund the Police. Adherents of this definition see defunding the police as a means of eliminating certain police departments as they currently exist and replacing them with new police departments from the ground up. This is essentially the Camden model; in 2012, the city of Camden, NJ disbanded its police department and rebuilt it based on a community-oriented policing model (although the history of this transition is often distorted). Those who follow this definition of defunding are inclined towards local change, seeking to maintain the framework of policing but completely rebuilding the local institution.

4.Demilitarize the Police

Another definition, similar to the reform definition, of Defund the Police focuses primarily on demilitarization. This definition of defunding, like the reform definition, is essentially describing reforms that have already occurred in the last decade and continue to be broadly supported.

Unlike the reform definition, the demilitarization definition quite literally means defund, just more narrowly defined than what others mean when they use the term defund. Compared to other definitions, this one includes a very specific policy proposal: defunding federal programs that give surplus military equipment to local police. Those who follow the demilitarization definition often want more than just that, of course, like defunding tactical narcotics units and warrior training. In short, proponents of this definition of defunding overall seek to cut

funding that enables the tools and culture of violence that they believe has proliferated in policing.

5.Re-focus and Replace the Police

The re-focus/replace definition of Defund the Police centers on shifting policing priorities away from quality of life and non-violent incidents, to focus primarily on violent crimes while allowing mental health and social work professionals to handle the former category of calls. Like the demilitarization definition, this definition may in fact be a subset of the reform definition. A key difference, however, is that the re-focus proponents are not necessarily working to reduce focus on non-violent incidents, but rather to change who responds to such incidents. In other words, re-focus/replace proponents seek to pull funding and authority for certain categories of calls away from traditional armed police and to hand it to other professionals who have greater specialization.

6.Not about the Police

The last definitional category for Defund the Police really has little to do with the institution of police itself. For this group of proponents, the focus is on investment in communities like education programs, employment opportunities, and affordable housing. This is not too far off from what proponents of other definitions suggest should be done with the funds taken from police. The key difference, however, is that those falling under this last category are really borrowing Defund the Police as a phrase to push for what they see as underfunded programs. Their focus is not really on challenging the institution of policing, but rather on other areas of the community; defunding the police is simply a means to an end.

Credits: Mike Von (@thevoncomplex, Unsplash)

The Internal Definitional Debate in Action

The internal debateas the various definitions demonstrateis not one of trivial semantics, but rather of substantive policy disagreements. This genuine divide in definitions among proponents of Defund the Police has become clearer in numerous examples of legislation and policy actions that were introduced during the 2020 wave of protests, but began to collapse soon after.

New York

The splinters in the Defund the Police movement became evident even as protests continued, as was the case with New York City in late June 2020. City officials had already been planning cuts to the New York Police Department (NYPD)s budget due to the coronavirus pandemic, but under pressure from ongoing protests, agreed to cut $1 billion of the NYPDs $6 billion budget. As New York Times reporters noted, the details seemed to please no one. The Councils vote to defund was more divided than usual, and there was clear dissatisfaction among council members and activists.

Some former city officials along with current elected officials criticized the move as being an insufficient effort to change policing in New York, calling it a trivial financial sleight of hand rather than a meaningful policy action.

Their criticisms ranged from the cuts not being large enough to the cuts not covering substantive NYPD programs.

Others disagreed with the move entirely, suggesting that outsiders were jeopardizing the very communities of color that they were purporting to help by calling for defunding the police. On the whole, it appeared that a plurality of council members and activists supported defunding the police, but disagreed widely on the policy actions. In many ways, this episode made clear the contradictory nature of the term Defund the Police: a term that has a seemingly self-evident definition really had no settled definition. As Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez paradoxically said at the time, [d]efunding police means defunding police.

Minneapolis

Other episodesincluding one at the epicenter of the 2020 protests, Minneapolisfurther demonstrated the presence of a contentious internal debate over the meaning of Defund the Police. Nine members of the largely progressive City Council responded to pressure from activists by publicly making a vague pledge at a Defund the Police rally. Their pledge, as The New York Times later reported, was an embrace of a police-free ideal [but]with no transition plan. However, it was clear that the nine city councilors who took the pledge did not uniformly support its words. Several councilors would later acknowledge their diverging interpretations of Defund the Police, with one going on to say, it was very clear that most of us had interpreted that language differently. The vague pledge to defund the Minneapolis Police Department (MPD) resulted in a hastily passed amendment to create a ballot initiative that would seek voters approval to abolish the MPD and hand off its authority to another agency.

Backlash was fierce and came from defunding activists who opposed the extreme nature of the proposal, activists who believed it did not go far enough, liberal moderates who opposed abolishing the police in lieu of reform, and external opponents like Donald Trump who were against any change. The Councils own constituents largely opposed the move, even as they supported police reform. The proposal failed to make it to the ballot in 2020 as it was blocked by the citys Charter Commission. Council members also seemed to walk back their pledges or at least their degree of support.

Nonetheless, they approved another vague ballot measure in July 2021this one brought by citizens via petitionthat would replace the Police Department with a Department of Public

Safety that employs a comprehensive public health approach, and which would include licensed peace officers (police officers) if necessary. This measure, which will go before voters in November 2021, appears to provide yet another contradictory policy definition of Defund the Police: defunding the police department and replacing it with a public safety department staffed by licensed peace officers.

Beyond

New York and Minneapolis are just two of a multitude of examples of the contentious internal debate among proponents of police reform and Defund the Police about what the term actually means, particularly when it comes to policy action. Other examples include:

clashes in Congress between progressive Democrats and moderate/traditional Democrats over what Defund the Police means and whether it is an appropriate slogan for what they believe it describes.

municipal budget changes in major cities across the country that cut funding to departments but did not reduce staffing levels, igniting backlash from activists who defined defunding as not merely cutting funds, but also reducing the size of departments and/or their authority.

fierce debate among academics about what defunding actually means and whether it would be effective or even necessary for achieving the purported goals of its proponents.

progressive public office candidates, like those in the New York mayoral race, walking back their support for Defund the Police or clarifying their interpretation of it amidst declining public support for defunding. One candidate in the New York race, Maya Wiley, attempted to walk back prior use of the term by saying, [t]he word means different things to different people[w]e should focus on the clarity of the demands.

Credits: Kayle Kaupanger (@notaphotographer, Unsplash)

The External Debate - Debating Facts Rather than Definitions and Merits

The external debate over defunding the policei.e., the debate between proponents of defunding and opponents of defunding largely played out during the 2020 election cycle. The sides to this debate were paradoxically both fluid and clear. They were fluid because support for defunding the police was not a partisan issue: the vast majority of people in both parties opposed defunding even at the time, and that number has only increased. Prominent liberals and Democrats opposed the slogan and the policies it suggested, including then-presidential candidate Joe Biden and senior members of the Democrats congressional caucus. Yet, attacks by Republicans and conservatives against what they painted as a concerted Democratic effort to abolish law enforcement in the United States helped to solidify, at least in rhetoric, the sides to the external debate. In other words, the narrative created by such attacks lumped Biden and the vast majority of liberals who opposed defunding in with the small group of progressives who supported it.

For their part, Biden and the Democrats sought to counterattack by suggesting that it was the Republicans, in fact, who wanted to defund the police. Thus a narrative and counternarrative

emerged, shaping an external debate that was heavily one-sided when it came to the actual merits of plans to defund the police (most people in both parties opposed them), but was clearly polarized when it came to rhetoric over who was actually trying to implement defunding (Republicans claimed it was all Democrats who were trying to defund; Democrats claimed that prominent Republicans were misleading the American public and were the people who were really defunding the police).

To be clear, this was not an even-handed both sides issue. The Republicans narrative was a precise, organized effort (with ads, speeches, etc.) while the Democrats counter-narrative was more of a weak impromptu rhetorical reaction by some prominent Democrats. For the most part, the Republican narrativethat Democrats were the ones defunding the police (which Republicans defined as blind cuts or abolition)was the prevailing one. Of course, which narrative prevailed does not really matter. When it comes to polarization, it does not take two to tango. Only one side has to succeed in its broad brushstrokes that lump the other side together, creating an in-out group divide. In other words, polarization could, and seemingly in fact did, result from just one side succeeding in stereotyping or generalizing the other side.

With no clear definition of Defund the Police, however, the result was not a debate centered over the merits because without a clear definition, it would be difficult to debate the merits of something. Rather the result was a debate centered over factual narratives: were the police being defunded and, if so, who was defunding them? The nuanced internal debate over the definition of defunding the police was flattened to mean blindly cutting funds to departments, or more often, to mean simply abolishing the police altogether.

The End Result

The impact of the void of definition when it comes to Defund the Police is not limited to discourse. Definitions, or lack thereof, shape discourse, which in turn affects policy implementation and outcomes. The lack of a consensus definition of Defund the Police arguably led to, or at least contributed to, electoral challenges for Democrats, political consequences for proponents of defunding, and implementation obstacles for defunding policies. As reporters live tweeted a congressional caucus conference call just days after the election, prominent Democrats were upset with their more progressive peers, blaming them for 2020 electoral losses, particularly in the House of Representatives. One such DemocratRep. Abigail Spanberger, a former federal law enforcement officerchastised her party: [d]ont say defund the police when that's not what we mean. Despite most Democrats opposition to Defund the Police, the failure to define the term, along with their support for non-defunding reforms, had seemingly enabled the success of the Republican narrative that Democrats were seeking to defund the police into oblivion. Many pointed to this narrative as the reason for the 2020 House losses for Democrats, and those lossesalong with the internal controversy produced in the Democratic Partymay well be one of the real world outcomes resulting from the void of definition of Defund the Police.

The lack of definition not only had electoral consequences for Democrats, but also political consequences for those who actually did support Defund the Police. As many have argued, the slogan, at best, may have impaired the changes sought by its supporters. Prominent figures, like those in the New York City Mayors race, who initially came out in support of defunding have been forced to walk back their statements. The lack of a clear definition of defunding, combined with the high risk for officials who tried to implement it as policy, led to awkward and vague policy changes. For example, budget changes for the Metropolitan Police Department in Washington, D.C. led to headlines asking, Did DC defund the police? and D.C. Police Budget: Does the Mayors Budget Defund the Police? Without a clear definition of Defund the Police, it is unclear whether these inconsistent budget changes constitute defunding. Indeed, it is difficult to even assess the success of defunding efforts because it is unclear what policy changes count as an attempt to defund the police.

Credits: Koshu Kunii (@koshuuu, Unsplash)

Nonetheless, it is increasingly apparent that changes made at the height of calls to defund are being reversed throughout the country. Given the Republican narrative that has defined Defund the Police as having an end goal of abolition and tied Democrats to it, as well as a surge of gun violence and homicides, it is increasingly less viable for officials to continue supporting defunding policies. As the Wall Street Journal reports, in the nations 20 largest local law-enforcement agencies, city and county leaders want funding increases for nine of the 12 departments where next years budgets already have been proposed. The increases range from 1% to nearly 6%. New York City officials will proceed with a $92 million police precinct construction project that had previously been cancelled due to COVID-19 budget cuts and pressure from defunding proponents. To hire more officers, Minneapolis restored $6.4 million to its police budget after having cut $8 million in 2020. In 2021, Baltimores new mayor sought to increase the city police departments budget by $27 million even though as a member of the city council, he had spearheaded a $22.4 million cut to the budget proposal from the previous year.

Oakland officials cut $29 million in 2020 but have already restored $3.3 million and are seeking to increase the police budget by $24 million. The list goes onstretching from Los Angeles to New York to Washington, D.C. In some cases, the reversals are due to concerns about the wave of gun violence and hate crimes. In others, they are due to administrative problems like staffing issues and even due to reform itself; as some opponents of defunding have argued, change can often require money. For example, Baltimore needs the additional funds in order to comply with a Justice Department consent decree. Overall, the result thus has been a collapse of supposed defunding policy: despite some successes, the defunding movement has largely failed to achieve sustained, consistent, identifiable policy change.

The Power of Meaning and The Meaning of Power

If one considers polarization to be a division of public opinion, then the Defund the Police controversy is a source of faux polarization; the majority of Americans oppose defunding, partisan narratives have painted a false picture of polarization. However, if one considers polarization to be more than just the actual division of public opinion, but to also include the perceived division of public opinion, then the Defund the Police controversy is a source of polarization. In all likelihood, the answer is probably both. What began initially as faux polarization has probably become a feedback loop, with false perceptions of polarization contributing to actual polarization. Republicans and conservatives increasingly oppose what they falsely believe to be a Democratic/liberal effort to Defund the Police. Democrats and liberals increasingly oppose what they see as a Republican/conservative effort to create a false narrative that they support defunding the police. Thus, faux polarization over the merits of defunding the police contributes to actual polarization over the factual reality about defunding: one side believes the other supports defunding while the other believes that that is just a deceitful political ploy. This, in turn, leads to cross-polarization, feeding into overall, broader polarization as Republicans and conservatives see this as yet another example of Democratic and liberal efforts to dismantle American institutions while Democrats and liberals see this as yet another example of Republican/conservative efforts to fabricate the truth.

Credits: Nathan Dumlao (@nate_dumlao, Unsplash)

That is not to suggest any normative judgement on Defund the Police or on its potential contribution to polarization. Indeed, the

failure to define Defund the Police is evidence in support of what some may argue is one of the strongest aspects of the defunding movement: decentralization. Like the Black Lives Matter movement in general, Defund the Police does not have a centralized leading figure, which simultaneously serves as a strength by allowing for a broader movement, but also makes it more difficult to effectively wield the power to define. Moreover, though polarization is often painted in a negative context, some political analysts have argued that fears over polarization are exaggerated and unnecessary. Indeed,

due to the lack of a consensus definition, Defund the Police proponents were unable to force a substantive debate over the merits of Defund the Police policies, but still succeeded in sustaining it on the national agenda. Many proponents may also find that they do not wish to be associated with those who do not take their demands to challenge systemic racism seriously; polarization helps people distance themselves from those who appear to disagree with their fundamental values. On the other hand, many Democrats did not take Defund the Police proponents seriously either, and a polarized discourse pushes aside the merits of the call to defund in favor of a partisan battle. In any case, regardless of the normative value of polarization, what is clear is that definitions can play a significant role in polarization by shaping discourse and shifting debates.

How things are defined matters. Political-social movements and coalitions are negotiations over meaning. When such negotiations fail to reach a solid consensus, external actors are able to exploit, intentionally or incidentally, the vagueness of meaning to impose their own definition, thereby freezing negotiation and polarizing discourse. In all likelihood, Defund the Police probably would have failed even with a clear consensus definition. Even given the wide range of interpretations, Americans repeatedly polled as opposed to defunding. In other words, even with the opportunity to interpret the term or call to action in the most favorable light, most Americans still opposed Defund the Police based on what they believed to be the basic policy premises of such a term. What is striking is not that Defund the Police has largely failed as a movement a year on, but rather that it has become another clashing point. Something

that was, and is even more so today, so broadly unpopular has seemingly become a point of contention and source of polarization.

The ongoing story of the Defund the Police movement is not unique. Political scientists have long described the

phenomenon of protest movements that take on a life of their own as the original organizers lose control of the narrative to broader society and mainstream media. Amidst growing partisan and ideological polarization in the United States, however, the Defund the Police case demonstrates how even issues on which there is a consensus opinion can become points of contention. If politics is defined as power relations or the struggle for power, then definitional debates about policy proposals like Defund the Police are inherently political: they are a struggle for the power to define. As this case demonstrates, in an era of hyper-polarization, the failure to successfully reach a consensus definitionto successfully wield the power to definemeans handing that power to define over to partisan opponents who can turn the debate away from merits and towards partisan factual disputes. This means that the failure to define serves not only as an obstacle to successful adoption and implementation of the policy, but also as a source of polarization.
